**Intution**
// There are two cases in which the robot never leaves a circle
1) After the first iteration, the final coordinates of Robot are same as initial coordinates (i.e. [0,0])
2) If after first iteration the final coordinates are different but it points in some other direction except North, then in that case it will return to its initial position([0,0]) after max 3 more iterations.
    2.1) Suppose after first iteration it points in East Direction (90 degree clockwise) then after second iteration it will point in South Direction (90 degree clockwise) then after third iteration in West then in fourth iteration in North Direction (back to its origin)
    2.2) Suppose after first iteration it points in South Direction (180 degree clockwise) then after second iteration it will point in North Direction (180 degree clockwise) then after third iteration in South then in fourth iteration in North Direction (back to its origin)
    2.3) Suppose after first iteration it points in West Direction (270 degree clockwise) then after second iteration it will point in South Direction (180 degree clockwise) then after third iteration in East then in fourth iteration in North Direction (back to its origin).

// There is one case in which robot will leave a circle    

 1. If robot points in North direction with different coordinates than its initial position after first iteration, then in second, third abd fourth iterations, it will continue to move forward inn north direction and will never comeback to origin

**Code Expanation**
Let the directions be
North = 0
East = 1
South = 2
West = 3

So if robot is facing in North and we move it left, then it points in East direction i.e i+1. (since north is 0 and east is 1)
   if robot is facing in North and we move it right, then it points in West direction i.e i+3. (since north is 0 and west is 3)

Generalising if we move the robot in Left then i=(i+1)%4
             if we move the ronot in Right then i=(i+3)%4
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isRobotBounded(string instructions) {        
        int x=0, y=0;
        int i = 0;
        vector<vector<int>>dir ={{0, 1}, {1, 0}, {0, -1}, {-1, 0}};
        for(auto it: instructions) {
            if(it=='G') { //Moving it in the direction its pointing by one step
                x+=dir[i][0];
                y+=dir[i][1];
            }
            else if(it=='L') { //changing the direction rotating it 270 degree clockwise
                i=(i+3)%4;
            }
            else if(it=='R') { //changing the direction rotating it 90 degree clockwise
                i=(i+1)%4;
            }
        }
        // After one iteration either it doesnt point in north direction or it returns back to its initial coordinates{0,0}
        return (i!=0) || (x==0 && y==0);
    }
};

```

